{"id":123,"date":"2004-06-02T09:44:57","date_gmt":"2004-06-02T17:44:57","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wordpress\/?p=123"},"modified":"2004-06-02T09:44:57","modified_gmt":"2004-06-02T17:44:57","slug":"enabling-freedom-of-expression","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/2004\/06\/enabling-freedom-of-expression\/","title":{"rendered":"enabling freedom of expression"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><a href=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/writing\/future-is-not-the-past\/future-is-not-the-past.html\">The Future of the Web is not the Past of Windows<\/a>: XML UI languages are commonly used to accelerate and simplify development and distribution of desktop-like applications. Languages like XUL and XWT encapsulate the set of Windows UI elements, and the ability to rapidly assemble a Windows-like Web application using XML is valuable and has many advantages over building a similar application in Visual Basic, let alone MFC or Swing. Unfortunately, using XML as a way to assemble interactive components that are defined using classic GUI toolkits leads to homogeneity and artificial simplicity, and does not reflect the diversity of today&#8217;s Web. Freedom of expression is essential for a UI markup language.<\/p>\n<p>Read the complete paper in <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/writing\/future-is-not-the-past\/future-is-not-the-past.html\">html<\/a> or <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/writing\/future-is-not-the-past\/w3c-futureofwebui.pdf\">PDF<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>I presented this position paper yesterday at <a href=\"http:\/\/www.w3.org\/2004\/04\/webapps-cdf-ws\/\">the W3C workshop on Web Applications and Compound Documents<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>Many thanks to my editor, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.davidtemkin.com\">David Temkin<\/a>, who also came up with the title.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The Future of the Web is not the Past of Windows: XML UI languages are commonly used to accelerate and simpli